04891nam a22008055i 9789814695169DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898146951697 a10.1355/97898146951692doi  a(DE-B1597)522102  a(OCoLC)1100441607  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aBUS0790002bisacsh0481pa330qDE-1011 aOuyyanont, Porphant, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrown Property Bureau in Thailand and Its Role in Political Economy /cPorphant Ouyyanont. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (47 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tCrown Property Bureau in Thailand and Its Role in Political Economy -- tCrown Property Bureau in Thailand and Its Role in Political Economy -- tAPPENDIX -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Crown Property Bureau (CPB) has long been ignored in Thai economic literature. However, the Bureau is a huge conglomerate and holding company, with an income in excess of 10 billion baht, and with links throughout the economy. It is also the largest landholder in the country. The history of the Bureau can be traced back to 1890, and by 1913 the two largest holdings were the Siam Commercial Bank (SCB) and the Siam Cement Company (SCC). These two enterprises remain the main sources of Bureau income, and, together with landholdings, form two of the three main financial pillars of the Bureau. Both the SCB and the SCC owe their establishment (in 1906 and 1913 respectively) largely to royal initiative and investment. The growth of the financial strength of the CPB was tied to the commercial and economic development of Bangkok and the Thai economy. After an inactive period between the wars, the Crown Property Bureau regained momentum after 1948. Much of this was due to the Directors of the CPB since then. The wealth of the CPB expanded in line with economic development after 1950 (including the growth of Bangkok) and with the prosperity and diversification of the major holdings, the SCB and SCC. The Asian economic crisis of 1997 had a significant effect on the financial position of the CPB, in particular due to the difficulties of the SCB and SCC. The crisis forced major changes in the strategies of the CPB and in the management and policies of the SCB and SCC. The CPB has been instrumental in developing and financing many royal projects, including those relating to the king’s “sufficiency economy” philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGovernment. 0aMonarchy—Thailand. 0aReal estate business—Thailand. 0aThailand. Crown Property Bureau. 4aGovernment and Business. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070099240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981469516940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814695169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814695169.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-070099-2  PP Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGru